In that case, the question should be, why am I attempting to convert one concrete type to another concrete type?<p>If you&#x27;re writing a program, you should use the same type, std::vector<char* >, everywhere.<p>If you&#x27;re writing a library, the API should avoid including container details in function parameters, and const and non-const T should be allowed.<p><pre><code>    template<typename Container>
    void foo1(Container const& c);

    template<typename Iterator>
    void foo2(Iterator first);

    template<typename Iterator>
    void foo3(Iterator first, Iterator last);

    template<typename Iterator>
    void foo4(Iterator first, std::size_t num);

    template<typename T>
    void foo5(std::vector<T> const& vec);

    void foo6(char const* const* first, std::size_t num);
</code></pre>
foo6 is a pretty good alternative here, imo:<p><pre><code>    std::vector<char*> vec(...);
    foo6(&vec.front(), vec.size());
</code></pre>
It would be cool if the compiler could figure templated type conversion out, but the crux of the issue is, as I understand it, that T<A> and T<A const> are not necessarily implemented the same way.<p>Also note that std::vector<std::string const> won&#x27;t compile -- it wouldn&#x27;t be copy-assignable -- so these issues mostly seem to arise specifically when dealing with C strings and/or C compatibility. And reinterpret_cast is amazingly helpful for porting from C.

I think the use of inline styles was simply to make the example more compact and readable than something like:<p><pre><code>  <style>
  .table-example { display: table; }
  .table-example div { display:table-cell;
    vertical-align:middle; }
  .table-example div div { margin-left:auto;
    margin-right:auto; }
  </style>

  <div class=&quot;table-example&quot;>
      <div>
        <div></div>
      </div>
  </div></code></pre>
